{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox settlement | official_name = Dosso | other_name = | image_skyline = Dosso maternity clinic visit 2008.jpg | imagesize = 300px | image_caption = Officials at the opening of the regional maternity hospital, 2008 | image_flag = | image_seal = | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = Niger | pushpin_label_position = bottom | pushpin_mapsize = 300 | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Niger | coordinates = {{coord|13|02|40|N|3|11|41|E|region:NE|display=inline,title}} | subdivision_type = Country | subdivision_name = [[Niger]] | subdivision_type1 = [[Regions of Niger|Region]] | subdivision_name1 = [[Dosso Region]] | subdivision_type2 = [[Departments of Niger|Department]] | subdivision_name2 = [[Dosso Department]] | subdivision_type3 = [[Communes of Niger|Urban Commune]] | subdivision_name3 = Dosso | established_title = | established_date = | government_type = | leader_title = | leader_name = | area_total_km2 = | area_land_km2 = | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = 227 | elevation_ft = 748 | population_footnotes = | population_total = 91488 | population_as_of = 2011 | population_density_km2 = | population_urban = | population_metro = | timezone = | utc_offset = | timezone_DST = [[West Africa Time|WAT]] | utc_offset_DST = +1 | postal_code_type = | postal_code = | area_code = | website = | footnotes =<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/NG/3/Dosso.html Dosso, Niger Page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081030063936/http://www.fallingrain.com/world/NG/3/Dosso.html |date=30 October 2008 }}. Falling Rain Genomics, Inc. 1996–2004. Accessed 2 June 2009</ref> }} '''Dosso''' is a city in the south-west corner of [[Niger]]. It lies {{convert|130|-|140|km}}<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/169756/Dosso Dosso], britannica.com.</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSL185227 Niger anti-referendum protests turn violent]. Adboulaye Massalatchi, Reuters. 1 June 2009.</ref> south-east of the capital [[Niamey]] at the junction of the main routes to [[Zinder]] and [[Benin]]. The seventh-most populous town in Niger and the largest in [[Dosso Region]], it had an official population during the 2001 census of 43,561.<ref>[http://www.citypopulation.de/Niger.html Population figures from citypopulation.de], citing [http://www.stat-niger.org/ (2001) Institut National de la Statistique du Niger].</ref> It is the capital of its region—which covers five departments in the southwestern corner of the nation, as well as of its own department: [[Dosso Department]]. The city itself lies at the centre of its own [[Communes of Niger|Urban Commune]].<ref>[http://www.case.ibimet.cnr.it/den/Documents/code_rural/cdrom/doc%20pdf/Loi%20N%B02002-14%20cr%E9ation%20des%20communes.pdf Loi n° 2002-014 du 11 JUIN 2002 portant création des communes et fixant le nom de leurs chefs-lieux]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. Includes list of 213 communes rurales and seats, 52 Communes urbaines and seats</ref>
==History== {{Main|Dosso Kingdom}} Dosso is the seat of the [[Dosso kingdom]], a Zarma chieftaincy which rose to dominate the entire Zarma region in Niger in pre-colonial Niger. The traditional ruler is called ''[[Zarmakoy]]'' or ''Djermakoy'' of Dosso, an autochthonous title meaning literally "King of Djermas" where ''koy'' means "king" in [[Zarma language|Zarma]] (or Djerma) language.
==Sites== Attractions in the town include the Djermakoy's palace and museum, nominated as a UNESCO [[World Heritage Site]] in 2006.<ref>[http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5041/ Palais du Zarmakoye de Dosso], 26 May 2006.</ref>
== Transport == The city of Dosso is a critical commercial hub through which transit import-export products from the [[Cotonou port]]. Due to this and its proximity to Niamey, Dosso is transportation hub. Dosso has an interim terminus of the [[Niamey]]–[[Cotonou]] railway presently{{When|date=November 2015}} under construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaysafrica.com/blog/2010/10/extending-from-benin-to-niger/ |accessdate=17 October 2010 |title=EXTENDING FROM BENIN TO NIGER | publisher = Railways Africa }}</ref> An extension to the capital, Niamey, would be a later stage.
In addition, there is a plan for the construction of a dry commercial port.
==Notable residents== * [[Rabiou Guero Gao]] – Olympic long-distance runner for Niger * [[Zakari Gourouza]] – first Nigerien Olympic judoka
