'''Jón Jónsson Aðils''' (25 April 1869, [[Reykjavík]] - 5 July 1920) was an Icelandic historian. He's been described as "Iceland's most prolific historian of the early twentieth century."<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halink|first=Simon|date=2017-01-01|title=Noble heathens: Jón Jónsson Aðils and the problem of Iceland's pagan past|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/nana.12319/abstract|journal=Nations and Nationalism|language=en|pages=n/a–n/a|doi=10.1111/nana.12319|issn=1469-8129}}</ref> Historians and political scientists argue that Aðils strongly shaped Icelandic nationalist discourse, and that his influence still affects Icelandic discourse on sovereignty issues, such as [[Accession of Iceland to the European Union|European integration]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=Sjálfstæð þjóð: trylltur skríll og landráðalýður|last=Bergmann|first=Eiríkur|publisher=|year=2011|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tandfebooks.com/isbn/9780203487570|title=Iceland and European Integration|work=Taylor & Francis eBooks|access-date=2017-04-04|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Middel|first=Kim|date=2018|title=Íslenzkt þjóðerni: Jón Jónsson Aðils’ Iceland and the road to the future|url=https://www.degruyter.com/view/j/ejss.2018.48.issue-2/ejss-2018-0013/ejss-2018-0013.xml|journal=European Journal of Scandinavian Studies|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1515/ejss-2018-0013|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Middel|first=Kim Peronne|title=The search for self-awareness: The road to national identity on Iceland, sæc. xiii-xx|date=2018|publisher=University of Groningen|url=https://www.rug.nl/research/portal/publications/the-search-for-selfawareness(3a1681b2-4d94-441d-a4d4-9828df91a694).html|language=English}}</ref>

== Historiography ==
He is known for distinguishing periods in [[History of Iceland|Icelandic history]] into golden ages, periods of decline and periods of humiliation. In Aðils’s narrative, the golden age begins with settlement in 874 (and reaches its high point during the Saga Age) and ends when Iceland falls under foreign rule (Jónsson 1903, 79, 88-89, 103, 105, 178).<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://landogsaga.is/section.php?id=7775&id_art=8179|title=Land og saga - Íslenzkt þjóðerni. Eftir Jón J. Aðils|website=landogsaga.is|access-date=2017-04-04}}</ref> Under foreign rule, the Icelandic nation declined and ultimately suffered humiliation (Jónsson 1903, 241-242).<ref name=":1" /><ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Bergmann|first=Eiríkur|date=2014-03-01|title=Iceland: A postimperial sovereignty project|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1177/0010836713514152|journal=Cooperation and Conflict|language=en|volume=49|issue=1|pages=33–54|doi=10.1177/0010836713514152|issn=0010-8367}}</ref> Aðils' lessons were that under Icelandic rule, the nation was prosperous, productive and artistic, but suffered under foreign role. However, Aðils argued that within every Icelander, a desire for freedom and nationalism remained, and only had to be awoken.<ref name=":1" /> Historian Guðmundur Hálfdanarson suggests that Aðils himself was doing his best to awaken this slumbering nationalist sentiment and strengthen the Icelandic pursuit of independence.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hálfdanarson|first=|year=2010|title=Sagan og sjálfsmynd(ir) íslenskrar þjóðar|url=|journal=Glíman|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> 

